Text.Value: You're even more of a fool to stand in my way now.
You gave them peace. For that, for all you have done, you have our thanks.
Well I expect you'll leave me in peace from now on.
If you want to fight, can we just get on with it?
You killed not only Cazador, but also his wretched creations. I expected less.
It had to be done.
Thank you, I only want to live in peace.
A fool I was, to ever hope a beast like you could be saved.
Perhaps today your intentions are good? Perhaps. But power twists people. Corrupts people. Convinces them to do terrible things for a 'greater good'.
For you, perhaps. Not for us.
But if you ever decide to hunt them, know they include your children.
We tracked you halfway across the Sword Coast, only to finally catch up with you here.
They're in the Underdark - they'll feed on the monsters down there.
I feared you would complete the ritual and we would face a new, more powerful foe. I am pleased to be wrong.
We do not wait for that to happen. We destroy evil here, today!
They were innocent - it would have been more evil to kill them.
You should know - Cazador may be dead, but there are still thousands of spawn locked up down there.
If such a time comes, if you need help, we will stand with you.
Perhaps, but innocent or not, they remain dangerous.
I had hoped to avoid this path. I had hoped you would choose the better road.
You didn't think I could do it? I'm hurt.
Your children among them...
I fear none of us will see peace yet. There are still trials ahead.
They - they survived?
Oh please, there's no need for such language. I promised you Cazador's death and I more than delivered.
I'm sorry I took your children, but Cazador's dead now. It's over.
I never doubted your ability to kill. But your ability to resist temptation? That I doubted.
Cazador may be gone, but there are still thousands of vampire spawn down there. Including your children.
I had no choice, I was a spawn, following orders.
And I hope I never see any of you again.
That depends on how you define 'survived', really, but they are free. They're making their way into the Underdark as we speak.
Thank you. And for what it's worth - I'm sorry. I wish I could return the ones I took from you.
...That's it? No reward?
If we turn our backs on evil like you, then my tribe is not worth saving.
With me - destroy the beast!

EditorData.NodeContext: Over her shoulder to the warriors behind her - calling them to join her in attacking you

Text.Value: And when the city is saved? Can you give up this power? Or do you look for the next battle? The next conquest?
We offer no gold, but we do give you a promise.
Once, perhaps. Now you're something else entirely.
Cazador is destroyed and his plans ruined. I was not sure you could do it.
Get out of my way. I'm in no mood to talk.
I am Ulma, of the Gur. You know my people. You helped your master bring us down.
I know you face trials ahead. But when it is time, you will not face them alone. We will stand with you as best we can.
Forgive me, I meant no disrespect.
For us, destroying evil is a simple choice. We are born to do it - trained to do it.
A fool I was, to ever hope a beast like you could be saved.
Walk away. Don't sacrifice what's left of your tribe for nothing.
I pray you are right. But if they leave to hunt on the surface, they will get no mercy from us.
They were innocents. To kill them would have been an even greater crime.
I admit, I had my doubts. I did not want to face a new, powerful vampire unarmed. I am pleased to be wrong.
Thank you for what you have done - slaying Cazador was a great justice. As for the rest... well, time will tell.
Until then, go in peace. And thank you.
You killed one vampire, but released seven thousand of his spawn? Have you lost all sense?
They - they were turned?

EditorData.NodeContext: just got the terrible news her tribes children were turned into vampires

Text.Value: Perhaps. But better a fool than a coward.
An unexpected wrinkle, but we shall tend to them. You have done enough.
Perhaps, but innocent or not, they remain dangerous.
And what do we find?
Hold there, vampire. We have business to settle.
Really? I'm hurt.
Your sins against us were great. But today, so were your deeds.
Don't you understand? With this power I can save the city!
This is... difficult news. We will need to decide what it means.
Cazador may be gone, but there are still thousands of vampire spawn down there.
So I can see from all your heavily-armed friends. You didn't think I could resist completing the ritual, did you?
Thank you for what you have done - slaying Cazador was a great justice. As for the rest... well, time will tell.
You killed not only Cazador, but also his wretched creations. I admit, I expected less.
But you have my people's thanks - when it is time for you to face those trials, we will stand with you.
One blood-sucking beast replaced with another. Our children sacrificed to birth a monster.
*You don't know the woman's name, but you recognise her face. You saw it in the firelight, twisted in rage and grief the night you stole her tribe's children.*
So? If you have a problem with it, go deal with it.
Slaying Cazador was a great justice. You have our thanks, now and forever.
For what it's worth, I'm sorry. I wish I could bring your children back.
Out of my way. I'm in no mood to talk.
Cazador is destroyed and his plans ruined. I was not sure you could do it.
Do not fear, they will be dealt with.
I promised I'd kill Cazador. Did I not deliver?
I did not come here to fight. I'd hoped to talk.
But to face your kin? To face everything you know and still make that choice. There is nothing simple there.
And your children helped me ascend to new power. How fitting.
You are free - never again will you be hunted by my people.
This is... difficult news. We will need to decide what it means.
I would not be so hasty. You have trials still to face - you may want allies.
We searched for you when we heard you were free, hoping you could help us undo the evil he started.
I had hoped to avoid this path. I had hoped you would choose the better road.
You think we will see one evil replaced by another? No.
You killed one vampire, but released seven thousand of his spawn? Have you lost all sense?
Yes, I set them free. Including your children - they're spawn too now.

Synopsis: Dialog with the Gur Leader after you defeated Cazador
